args: Whaddya say we get some more\nR & R before headin' back,\n{player_name}?
Why not? You've got to stop and smell the\nroses every now and... Hmm?
Standin' at a cliff's edge... Distant gaze...\nI don't like where this is goin'.
Hear that?! Okay, I REALLY don't like\nwhere this is goin'!
DON'T DO IT, LADY! THERE'S SO MUCH\nTO LIVE FOOOOOOOOOOOR!
Ohhh my! What a pretty butterfly!
Oof, that's gonna sting... Ahem...\nDon't do anythin' rash, lady.
I beg your pardon? Rash?\nWhat do you mean?
What do I...? Uhh, I came running 'cause\nI thought ya were about to fling\nyerself over the edge here.
Oh, goodness. I'm sorry to have given you\nthe wrong idea.
So you were just enjoyin' the view?\nMuttering in a darkly philosophical way?\nSheesh, talk about misleadin'.
Seems to me like you have something on\nyour mind. We'd be happy to listen, if so.
V-very well. My name is Xania.\nI am a mage.
Until recently, I lived with my little brother\non the family pumpkin farm. But when he\nmarried, I decided to strike out on my own.
Didn't get along with the wife?
It's just that ever since our parents died,\nI'd been looking after him.
But now his wife... Well, she's amazing,\nfrankly. She takes care of everything.
And you felt like you didn't have a role\nto play anymore?
It's got me wondering what my life\nis even for.
Heh. It's easy to get lost sometimes.\nSo now yer on a journey to find yerself\nagain, yeah?
During my travels, I'm hoping to complete\nthe book my father started writing.
Is that the one there?\nï¼‚Better Living Through Spellcraftï¼‚?
Your father was a mage too, then?
That's right. He worked for the town hall,\nusing magic to construct flood protection,\ntreat illnesses, things of that nature.
He wanted to gather those spells into one\ntome so that others could make use of\nthem...but passed shortly after he began.
I may be biased, but I believe the ideas\nfor spells in his notes are quite unique.\nSadly, the book is mostly incomplete.
So I took it upon myself to conduct\nmy own experiments and record my\nresults until his book is finished.
That's really somethin', you honorin'\nhis memory like that.
The first line of his manuscript simply\ngrabbed hold of me, and I knew I had\nto finish it.
ï¼‚Life is the endless struggle for peace.ï¼‚\nI see what you mean. That's lovely.
It's perplexing. He was just an ordinary\nlocal official. I'd never heard him speak\nof war or fighting once.
So the curiosity's eatin' at ya?
I can't help but feel as though I'll learn\nthe reason if I can finish his manuscript.
And that maybe I'll find my own answer \nfor what life is along the way.
Well, hey, havin' a goal's important.
Agreed. Fortune saw fit to cross\nour paths here. If there's any way\nI can help you, let me know.
In that case, I do have one question.\nI've heard of someone in these parts\nfighting for peace with body and soul.
I think if I'm ever going to understand\nwhat my father meant, it will be\nfrom observing someone like that.
Apparently their name is\n{player_name}, but no one\nseems to know where to findâ€”
HAH! Bwaaa ha ha ha! Ya wanna talk\nabout fortune? How crazy is that?!
